<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUN 93 / NFC may drop results forecast
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANGUS FOSTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TRANSPORT and logistics company NFC, an experiment in popular capitalism
since its 1982 employee-led buy-out from the government, is considering
ending its unique practice of giving 'best view' forecasts of future
profits.
The practice was developed to keep shareholder employees informed before the
company was listed on the stock market.
When the company floated in 1989, it won special permission from the stock
exchange to keep the 'best view' practice because about 90 per cent of its
33,000 employees were also shareholders, but many were not familiar with
owning shares.
The practice is under review because of changing rules about communicating
information to shareholders.
The company is also concerned about possible legal challenges in the US if
it failed to meet its best view forecast.
NFC yesterday reported pre-tax profits more than doubled to Pounds 86.6m in
the 28 weeks to April 17.
Most of the increase was due to exceptional profits on a disposal and the
results were slightly below expectations.
The company is sticking to its earlier 'best view' estimate for this year of
Pounds 95m to Pounds 100m, excluding exceptional gains.
The review of 'best view' forecasts also reflects NFC's growing
international businesses, which are more prone to economic and currency
swings. Overseas earnings have grown from almost nothing 10 years ago to 45
per cent.
According to analysts, the review also signals NFC's desire to come into
line with other large transport groups, especially as institutions now own
more than 50 per cent of its shares.
Some analysts expect NFC to launch its first rights issue if a suitable
acquisition arises.
Lex, Page 22; Background, Page 24
</TEXT>
