<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUN 93 / Observer: Departridge
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
His 10 years at the head of the Bank of England, said Robin Leigh-Pemberton
at the Guildhall on Tuesday, had been a bit like the 12 days of Christmas:
'Twelve economies diverging. Eleven Lord Mayors presiding. Ten select
committee MPs a-questioning. Nine ERM members a-realigning. Eight trade
secretaries a-trading places. Seven wise men arguing. Six chief secretaries
cutting. Five monetary aggregates. Four chancellors of the exchequer. Three
deputy governors. Two prime ministers. And one Governor of the Bank of
England.'
