<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUN 93 / Observer: The City's dressing down
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Hands up all those who turned up at the Lord Mayor's Guildhall dinner this
week minus their white tie. Is the outbreak of black ties amongst the
bankers and merchants yet another sorry sign of the way standards are
slipping in the Square Mile?
To a degree, Celestria Noel, social editor of Harpers &amp; Queen, sympathises
with confused guests, especially those who came from out of town. The invite
specified evening dress and decorations. Not a word about white ties. 'You
can wear decorations with black tie. They should have stipulated white tie,'
Noel opines.
As the author of Jennifer's diary a well-studied arbiter of good form, Noel
is infinitely more concerned by the faux pas of the 'children of the
sixties' now inhabiting positions of power than unsophisticated foreign
bankers. 'People wear what they like these days,' sighs Noel. Buckingham
Palace, it seems, is about the only place left where people dare not wear
the wrong coloured bow.
</TEXT>
