<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUN 93 / MoD is criticised over ship refits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WHITE, Defence Correspondent and ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE MINISTRY of Defence's handling of naval vessel refitting was criticised
by MPs yesterday as the service's privately managed dockyards awaited a
crucial government decision on their future.
The Commons public accounts committee complained of slow progress in
changing procedures at the Devonport and Rosyth dockyards since management
was transferred to private consortia in 1987.
The cabinet will decide shortly which yard should service the new Trident
submarines. The decision - not expected until next week at the earliest -
will mean concentrating all work on refitting and refuelling nuclear-powered
submarines on one site. Thousands of jobs are at stake in Devon, Cornwall,
and Fife.
The cross-party committee, chaired by Labour MP Mr Robert Sheldon, said
reductions in the Navy's refitting programme and short-notice changes had
made it difficult for the new managers to operate on a commercial basis.
Faster progress should have been made in tightening specifications for work
at the yards, the committee said.
'Poor specification of the work to be undertaken in refits has contributed
to difficult contract negotiations, excessive extra work, delays and cost
increases,' the committee's report found. It criticised 'deficiencies' in
the system for procuring materials, most of which were still supplied to the
yards by the Navy.
'This is a legacy of history, but it is not appropriate for a commercial
regime,' the report said.
The report also attacked Pounds 137m worth of 'abortive expenditure' on two
submarines, which the ministry decided to decommission in 1990 while the
submarines were both in refit. The cross-party campaign among MPs trying to
ensure that Rosyth dockyard wins the Trident contract stepped up its efforts
yesterday, Alison Smith writes.
Mr Gordon Brown, the shadow chancellor, is to meet Mr John Major today and
will give the prime minister a copy of the report setting out Rosyth's case.
His Dunfermline East constituency includes Rosyth.
Devonport is widely regarded at Westminster as the front-runner but several
Scottish Conservatives have indicated that they would be prepared to vote
against the government if Devonport wins.
Committee of Public Accounts, 39th Report, Ministry of Defence: Operation of
the Royal Dockyards under Commercial Management. HMSO. Pounds 12.15.
</TEXT>
