<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUN 93 / Parliament and Politics: Fowler tries to defuse funds row
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN, IVOR OWEN and ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CONSERVATIVE party has received no money from the governments or ruling
families of Saudi Arabia, Kuwait or Brunei, Sir Norman Fowler indicated
yesterday, as he tried to defuse the row over the party's funding.
The Tory chairman spelt out four categories of donations the party would not
accept.
He told the home affairs committee his party would refuse any donation to
which strings were attached; which the party had reason to believe contained
illegally obtained monies; which came from a foreign government; or which it
did not know the source of.
He sidestepped questions about alleged donations from other individuals
including Mr John Latsis, the Greek shipping tycoon, and Mr Li Ka-Shing, the
Hong Kong businessman. 'We don't reveal details of people . . who make
contributions,' he said.
As Labour stepped up its attacks over the Pounds 440,000 in contributions
the Tories have admitted receiving from companies controlled by Mr Asil
Nadir, the fugitive businessman, Sir Norman said the party accepted the
money 'in good faith.' 'Contributions made do not buy influence in the
affairs of the Conservative party,' he said.
Sir Norman's comments came as Mr John Smith, the Labour leader, called on
the Conservatives to repay Mr Nadir's donations, claiming the issue 'is now
a matter for serious public concern'.
Labour plans to pursue the subject further next Tuesday by arranging a
Commons debate on the 'secrecy' of Conservative party funding. The party
said it was 'not going to let this matter rest.'
Yesterday, a Labour backbencher's bill designed to shed more light on
Conservative party finance cleared its first parliamentary hurdle, although
it has virtually no chance of becoming law.
Meanwhile, the TUC added its voice to calls for tighter controls over
political donations by companies. Trade unions last year spent Pounds 8m
from 'political funds' on non-party political activities, in addition to the
Pounds 8m they gave Labour, it disclosed.
Questioned on whether his statement that the Conservative party had had no
donations from the governments of Saudi Arabia or Kuwait included
contributions from the respective royal families, Sir Norman said: 'Yes, I
think that would also apply.'
He said he was 'totally opposed' to the direct state funding of political
parties. In a written submission to the committee, the party argued state
funding would 'either unduly favour established parties or encourage the
formation and growth of extremist parties.'
</TEXT>
