<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUN 93 / Parliament and Politics: Tough task for spending committee
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CABINET will today launch this year's public spending round by setting
up a powerful cabinet committee that includes Mr Michael Howard, the home
secretary, to oversee negotiations between the Treasury and spending
departments.
The EDX committee is expected to be given a tough remit at today's meeting,
with ministers expected to agree public spending should not exceed the
Pounds 253.6bn ceiling set for 1994-95.
The inclusion of Mr Howard, regarded at Westminster as likely to back harsh
spending curbs rather than tax increases, will help appease rightwingers in
the Tory party.
Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, is expected to give a bleak outlook for
public finances in the year ahead, emphasising that he does not believe that
Britain's Pounds 50bn annual deficit can be reduced only by economic growth.
He will warn colleagues that extra spending in the next financial year by
one department will have to be offset by savings elsewhere.
Mr Clarke has emphasised that no Tory would want to raise taxes merely
because the government had failed to tackle properly the scale of public
spending. He has also made clear his view that there are areas of
expenditure where there is plenty of room for downward pressure.
With the debate within the Conservative party over tax and expenditure plans
likely to last throughout the summer, Mr John Smith, Labour leader, warned
yesterday that the government 'has declared war on the welfare state'.
He told the annual conference of the health service union Cohse: 'When faced
with the failure of their economic policies they don't consider closing tax
loopholes for the rich . . . they penalise people on Invalidity Benefit.'
Mr Peter Lilley, social security secretary, responded that the public
spending review 'will produce a better system that protects the most
vulnerable whilst being affordable'.
</TEXT>
