FT  17 JUN 93 / Parliament and Politics: PM and Reynolds hold Ulster talks
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR sought last night to persuade Unionists to rejoin talks on
Ulster's future, saying an 'early objective' would be 'to re-affirm in
Northern Ireland the sort of democratic structures most people would want to
enjoy'.
Speaking after talks with Mr Albert Reynolds, the Irish prime minister, he
made clear that the two governments would not impose a solution on the
province. The search for a lasting agreement via talks 'is a matter for
persuasion and patience,' he said.
Although he played up the prospects of a political reform in the province -
the main ambition of unionists - the prime minister said the government
still wanted a 'three-stranded' approach, also covering institutions linking
north and south Ireland, and London with Dublin.
Mr Reynolds said the two governments did not expect a resumption of round
table talks until the autumn.
