<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUN 93 / Parliament and Politics: Howard allows police to test
truncheon alternative
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR MICHAEL HOWARD yes-terday used his first speech as home secretary to
accept a police request that new batons should be tested as a replacement
for truncheons. But he also signalled a fresh approach for the Tories on
crime prevention.
In a speech to senior police officers, Mr Howard adopted language previously
more familiar to the Labour party, saying he felt 'passionately that we must
do everything we can to build a strong and effective partnership between the
police and the public'.
Mr Howard also indicated that he was keen to steer away from the
confrontational style of his predecessor Mr Kenneth Clarke, and that he
wanted to co-operate with police forces in enhancing the role of local
police authorities.
Trips to police stations have been a high priority for Mr Howard. He spent
Tuesday night on patrol with the Metropolitan Police in Brixton.
Local police authorities are to be given responsibility for setting their
own budgets and will draw up with the chief constable local policing plans
setting out priorities and how they will be met, Mr Howard said.
He said responsibility should be devolved as far as possible so that police
officers closest to the problems can do their job with the minimum of
interference. A white paper on the organisation, structure and management of
the police service will be published soon by the Home Office.
Mr Howard said that an effective partnership between the police and the
public would give the 'best possible' chance of fighting crime
successful-ly.
He announced that an new side-handled baton was to be tested in an effort to
give more protection to the police, particularly to women officers. The
baton is collapsible, meaning it is less conspicuous to carry than rigid
versions.
Mr Tony Blair, the shadow home secretary, said the move was, 'sensible,
particularly because of the problems policewomen are facing - with
increasing numbers of attacks on them'.
</TEXT>
