FT  17 JUN 93 / Parliament and Politics: Hurd condemns Bosnia pressure
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR DOUGLAS HURD, the foreign secretary, yesterday condemned unrealistic
demands for action by the European Community and its allies to ensure
compliance with UN security council decisions by the warring factions in
Bosnia, Ivor Owen writes.
In question-time exchanges in the Commons, he also warned that if British
and other troops had to be withdrawn because of unacceptable risks to their
safety a 'massacre' would probably follow.
Mr Jack Cunningham, the shadow foreign secretary, described the recent
Washington agreement as 'deeply flawed' because it gave clear signals to
Serbia that its aggression would be rewarded by extra territory. Mr Hurd
accused Mr Cunningham of resorting to a 'something must be done' approach,
and said it was the least useful advice that could be given in present
circumstances.
