<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUN 93 / Vodafone steps up price war
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE DEVELOPING mobile phone price war was further fuelled yesterday when
Vodafone, the largest mobile operator, published tariffs for new and
existing services.
Vodafone's new local digital service, to be launched in October, will
feature a 20p a minute peak-rate tariff for calls in local call zones that
offer the service, including the '071' London zone.
A London tariff of 33p a minute applies under its existing 'analogue'
network, which will operate in parallel with the new digital networks. That
tariff, in turn, is to be cut to 25p - in line with the present provincial
tariff.
The tariffs are partly a response to the imminent launch of a PCN service by
Mercury One-2-One, a joint venture between Cable &amp; Wireless and US West.
One-2-One is testing its service, which will be launched within the M25 area
later this summer at a peak-rate tariff of less than 20p a minute.
Vodafone is launching two advanced digital networks this autumn. The local
network, called MetroDigital and to be launched on October 1, will cover the
zone within the M25 and other parts of the south-east.
By the end of 1994, MetroDigital will cover all British centres with
populations of more than 4,000.
In September a pan-European digital network, called EuroDigital, will come
into service. Built to the pan-European digital standard - known as GSM - it
will allow subscribers to make or receive calls on the same digital handset
in all the main European Community and Scandinavian countries.
Considered alongside moves made or expected by other operators, yesterday's
announcement marks the biggest shake-up in the UK mobile market since the
start of cellular services in 1985.
Mr Chris Gent, Vodafone's managing director, described the new tariffs as
'appropriately competitive'.
However, with pre-tax profits of Pounds 322.5m last year, representing a
remarkable 46 per cent of sales income, analysts believe Vodafone could be
forced to reduce prices further if the competitive pressure intensifies.
Handsets for the new digital networks will retail for about Pounds 400,
double the cost of those for the existing analogue network.
</TEXT>
