<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUN 93 / School finance practices are questioned
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE 'GREEN shoots' of impropriety have appeared in locally managed schools
in England and Wales, says a report published today by the Audit Commission.
The report includes examples of questionable financial practice.
Most schools have taken well to managing their own finances, it says, but
problems were found with both grant-maintained schools and those still under
local education authority control. Locally managed schools are those with
budgets devolved from local education authorities and grant-maintained
schools that have opted-out.
All the schools surveyed had increased their levels of administrative staff.
However, there were wide variations in the amount of time and money spent on
administration. For example, one primary school with 183 pupils paid for 646
administrator's hours in one year, while another with 198 pupils paid for
2,886 hours.
Examples of questionable practice included the husband of a member of a
school's staff who was given repair work even though his quote was Pounds
2,500 above the lowest, and a head teacher who employed her daughter on
'much higher' than normal wages without telling the governors.
In one case, a contract for repair work was given to a company owned by a
friend of a governor even though there was a lower bid.
Mr Bob Chilton, a director of the Audit Commission, pointed out that
grant-maintained schools were 'almost unique' among public-sector bodies in
being allowed to appoint their own external auditors. He said: 'There's a
danger of fear and favour becoming involved.'
The report also revealed a trend for pupil-teacher ratios to rise after
schools took control of their own management. It attributed this to rising
salary demands from staff, and added: 'In order to keep expenditure within
means, schools have not increased teacher numbers commensurately with an
increase in pupil numbers.'
The commission visited 100 schools which had had devolved budgets for at
least two years.
Adding up the Sums: Schools' Management of their Finances. HMSO. Pounds
8.00.
</TEXT>
<XX>
