<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUN 93 / Rule changes for open-ended funds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Financial Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ACTIVE LOBBYING by the Association of Unit Trusts and Investment Funds has
been rewarded by three government concessions on the taxation and structure
of open-ended investment funds.
First, an anomaly introduced in the March Budget by the changes to advance
corporation tax (ACT) is to be removed by an amendment to the 1993 Finance
Bill now going through parliament.
The ACT changes in the Budget threatened to impose, in an unintended way,
extra taxation on life assurance companies and other corporate owners of
unit trusts. As life companies own unit trusts worth some Pounds 30bn, or 40
per cent of the total funds assets of the unit trust industry, they might
have been forced to liquidate their holdings.
Now, a 'streaming' arrangement will permit UK company dividends to be taxed
differently from other income, including interest on deposits or bonds. As a
result life companies will pay no extra tax.
The same streaming device is to be used to permit unit trusts to pay
interest and other non-UK dividend income to foreign investors without
deduction of tax. Legislation for this is promised by the Treasury for the
next Finance Bill, due towards the end of the year.
The move will enable UK unit trust companies to market bond funds and money
funds (but not equity funds) to non-UK residents on a more equal footing to
companies based in low-tax centres such as Luxembourg and Dublin.
The third concession is a commitment to issue a discussion document before
the end of the year on the introduction of open-ended investment companies.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
