<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUN 93 / Managers seen to be missing the IT message
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LUCY KELLAWAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH managers are drowning in paper and surrounded by fancy technology
they do not know how to use. They are spending ever more time in meetings
and sending each other increasing numbers of meaningless memos, a study has
found.
The Institute of Management and Aspen Business Communications investigated
the tangled lines of communication inside British companies and Mr Roger
Young, institute director-general, said the results were 'depressing'.
He added that managers were 'resorting to the tools of Dickens to
communicate with each other'.
The survey showed that less than 15 per cent of the 700 managers surveyed
understood the potential of their IT systems, and only half thought their
system was installed in a sensible fashion.
The survey questioned the conventional wisdom that communication had
improved as a result of the restructuring of British companies from
hierarchical to 'flatter' structures. The idea was that flatter companies
would mean easier and faster communications, with managers given more
authority to make decisions.
But more than 40 per cent of the managers said they were sending and
receiving more memos than before, while two thirds were spending more time
in meetings. Only four-in-10 said their company communications strategy was
clearer than before.
Respondents complained that the cutting out of the old layers of management
had made their organisations less caring. More than half said they had
become more accountable in their jobs, but had not been given the
corresponding authority to take decisions. However, most agreed that the
shift from paternalistic management had the positive effect of making their
companies more open, informal and progress-ive.
Most managers reported that the introduction of technology had speeded the
flow of information through the company, and had increased their access to
it. However, only four in 10 said it had improved its relevance. 'Much of
the information is poorly targeted and of little relevance to the
recipient,' said Mr Young.
In spite of the elevation in the role of the memo, less than half the
respondents thought it an effective way of communication. Over two thirds
said that to talk to someone face-to-face was more effective than to
communicate on paper or technology.
Are Managers Getting the Message? IM Books, Burston Distribution Services,
2a Newbridge Trading Estate, Whitby Road, Bristol BS4 4AX. Pounds 15 for IM
members, Pounds 30 for non-members.
</TEXT>
