<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUN 93 / Brewers angry at Customs statement
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP RAWSTORNE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE ROW between Customs and Excise officials and the Brewers' Society broke
out again yesterday over Customs' statements that the new system of beer
duty introduced earlier this month would not penalise brewers but bring them
'a bonus of millions', Philip Rawstorne writes.
Brewers protested two weeks ago that the system - under which duty is
charged on the alcoholic strength of the finished product - would increase
the industry's tax burden by Pounds 64m a year.
Bass, Courage, and Carlsberg-Tetley, the three leading brewers, announced
reductions in the strength of a number of beer brands to ease the impact.
Customs and Excise said that switching the duty charge from an earlier
production stage would produce a one-off cashflow benefit to the industry of
Pounds 200m.
Mr Robin Simpson, the society's director, said the Customs statement was
'absolutely outrageous'. He added: 'The one-off benefit to brewers comes
from paying duty a few weeks later. To suggest this offsets in any
significant way an increase of 3 per cent in the industry's taxation bill is
blatantly misleading.'
</TEXT>
