<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUN 93 / Share options put under spotlight
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LUCY KELLAWAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE EXERCISING of share options by directors would have been significantly
curbed if guidelines being considered by institutional investors had been in
force in 1991 and 1992, says research by Incomes Data Services published
today.
Institutional investors have been increasingly concerned about generous
remuneration packages for directors, and have turned their attention to
share option schemes, which require shareholders' approval.
Guidelines suggested by the National Association of Pension Funds say
options should be exercised only if the rise in the company's share price at
least matched the rise in the FT-A All-Share Index over the option period.
According to the June issue of IDS Management Pay Review, one-in-five
options exercised by directors of top companies during two quarters in 1991
and 1992 would have been disallowed by the association's guidelines.
The National Association of Pension Funds and the Association of British
Insurers disagree over how tough guidelines should be. They have delayed
until next month their announcement of joint guidelines on share options as
the main part of their platform for curbing excesses in directors' pay.
IDS, 193 St John Street, London EC1V 4LS. By subscription.
</TEXT>
