<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUN 93 / Market testing process attacked
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A SENIOR manager of a French company which yesterday won the first
significant contract in the market testing programme for contracting-out
Civil Service functions has attacked the way the process is being operated.
Mr Charles Cox, a director of computing services company Hoskyns, warned
that the programme's objectives were being prejudiced by unrealistically
framed tenders.
Private-sector interest would wither unless companies could see better
opportunities for profit, he said.
Mr Cox, director of Hoskyns' public-sector division, said policymakers and
civil servants had a poor understanding of the benefits of contracting out
services to the private sector.
'Tenders are often framed in such a way that the scope for suppliers to
deliver savings and still make an adequate return is very limited,' he said.
Hoskyns, the UK arm of Cap Gemini Sogeti, Europe's largest computing
services company, has been awarded the contract to run the Ministry of
Defence's Operations West Data Centre in Devizes, Wiltshire. It won against
competition from the Anglo-French Sema Group and an in-house bid.
The company has revenues of about Pounds 100m a year from outsourcing or
facilities management contracts.
Some 60 staff at the Devizes centre will be transferred to Hoskyns' payroll.
