<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUN 93 / Nissan Motor behind alleged Pounds 97m fraud, court told
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NISSAN MOTOR Corporation, the Japanese carmaker, was behind an alleged
Pounds 97m tax fraud on the Inland Revenue, the Old Bailey was told
yesterday.
The claim was made by Mr Michael Sherrard QC in his closing defence speech
on behalf on Mr Michael Hunt, the director of British car importer Nissan
UK.
The prosecution alleges that Mr Hunt was part of a fraud in which Nissan UK
executives conspired with shipping agents to overstate freight charges for
transporting the cars in an attempt to avoid corporation tax. More than
Pounds 200m was siphoned off and eventually laundered into two Swiss bank
accounts, including one at Credit Suisse, it is alleged. Mr Hunt, who did
not give evidence, denies the charges.
A fraud on the Revenue had plainly taken place, Mr Sherrard said. However,
the evidence showed there was a 'more than credible' case that it was the
Japanese, rather than the British, company that was responsible.
Documentary evidence of this was provided in a letter written in the early
1980s by Mr Seisaku Homma, then managing director of Nissan Motor Car
Carrier (NMCC), the carmaker's transport division, Mr Sherrard said.
The letter was written while the Dutch tax authorities were investigating
Autocontex, one of the shipping agents allegedly involved in the fraud. In
it, Mr Homma stated that all the money paid into the Credit Suisse account
was used to settle NMCC's transport accounts.
Mr Sherrard said the purpose of the Swiss bank account remained unknown.
'Were they assembling a corporate slush fund to buy their way into markets
throughout the world? We don't know,' he told the jury. However, the fact
was that the Japanese involvement in the fraud was real, he said.
Mr Hunt had made diary entries about his meetings with his alleged
co-conspirators, Mr Sherrard said. He would have been 'half-witted' to do
that if he was part of a fraud.
The Japanese, on the other hand, did not take any risks. Those that had
given evidence had not been able to produce any documents worth talking
about, Mr Sherrard said.
The trial continues today.
</TEXT>
