<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUN 93 / EC states agree telecoms reform: Liberalisation package
brings another denial of two-speed Europe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LUXEMBOURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A MINIMUM of six EC countries, including the largest member states, agreed
last night to open all domestic and international telephone calls to
competition by January 1, 1998.
But poorer and smaller countries have won between two and five more years to
adapt to the liberalised system.
EC telecoms ministers, meeting in Luxembourg, postponed discussion of
European Commission plans to allow certain groups of users access to
alternative networks for ordinary phone calls.
Mr Arne Melchior, the Danish minister who chaired the meeting, said after
the eight-hour discussion that the deal was not another example of a
'two-speed Europe' with richer member states, including Britain, France, and
Germany forging ahead of their partners. 'We want everyone to be on board,
but we are realistic enough to take account of the factual situation,' he
said.
Earlier, Mr Martin Bangemann, the EC's industry commissioner, warned member
states that it would be against their own interests to postpone the
Commission's proposed 1998 deadline for opening all telephone calls to full
competition. The plan is supposed to reduce telephone charges across the
Community, particularly for international and intra-EC calls. The Commission
has yet to agree formal draft legislation to liberalise so-called 'voice
telephony', so yesterday's meeting produced only a broadly worded
resolution.
Before July 1996 Brussels must come up with draft measures laying out the
regulatory framework for liberalisation, and in the meantime it is to 'work
closely' with the less developed countries to accelerate the modernisation
of their telephone systems.
At yesterday's meeting Luxembourg and Belgium asked to be classified as
'very small networks', which would not have to liberalise telephone services
until the year 2000. Less developed networks - Ireland, Spain, Portugal and
Greece - would benefit from an automatic postponement of the deadline until
2003 to allow them to modernise their infrastructure.
The Commission said it was pleased with the outcome of yesterday's meeting,
but it marks a step back from Brussels' original ambitious plans, which
followed earlier liberalisation of the market for telecoms equipment and
specialised services. Internal pressure had already forced Brussels to drop
an earlier plan to liberalise cross-border telephone calls within the EC by
1996 before moving to full competition by 1998.
</TEXT>
<XX>
