<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUN 93 / Goldman fined over Maxwell share deals: US bank negotiates
Pounds 160,000 settlement with securities body
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN and BRONWEN MADDOX
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GOLDMAN SACHS, the blue-chip US-based investment bank that dealt extensively
with companies controlled by the late Robert Maxwell, has been fined Pounds
160,000 by regulators for breaches of UK securities rules, and ordered to
pay an estimated Pounds 125,000 in costs.
This follows the fines imposed two weeks ago on Invesco MIM, the fund
manager, by Imro, the industry overseer, for irregularities in the
management of Maxwell pension funds.
Yesterday's fine on Goldman by the Securities and Futures Authority, the
self-regulatory body for the brokerage industry, is the first official
censure of Goldman Sachs' activities in relation to Mr Maxwell and the
largest fine ever imposed on a firm by the SFA.
The charges relate to share deals the SFA describes as 'free payments' to
Maxwell companies. The payments occurred during a time when it is now known
that Mr Maxwell's companies were frantically trying to raise cash.
The SFA said that its review did not conclude that 'Goldman Sachs or any of
its personnel participated in any illicit conduct with, or were aware of
illicit conduct by, Maxwell or any entity controlled by or associated with
him'.
Yesterday's fine does not rule out further actions against the investment
bank by the SFA or any other bodies.
Goldman Sachs was a party in transactions that have been the subject of
investigations by the Department of Trade and Industry, the Stock Exchange
and the Serious Fraud Office.
Goldman Sachs had asked that findings should not go to a tribunal as is
normal when rule breaches are uncovered. Instead, it sought a negotiated
settlement with regulators that resulted in the public announcement and
fine. It is understood that some findings have been sent to the US
Securities and Exchange Commission for review.
The rule breaches relate to three transactions, two of which were purchases
of roughly Pounds 24m in securities from Maxwell-controlled fund management
companies that invested assets on behalf of pension scheme members. The
third entity was Bishopsgate Investment Trust, a company at the heart of Mr
Maxwell's private interests. The company sold an estimated Pounds 25m in
securities to Goldman Sachs just months before Mr Maxwell's death.
The SFA said it concluded that in those three transactions, Goldman Sachs
had paid for, but failed to receive, all the shares involved. In effect, the
SFA said, Goldman Sachs made 'free payments' to Maxwell entities and failed
to tell regulators about the effect on its capital position.
Yesterday, Goldman Sachs emphasised that regulators had not concluded that
it engaged in or knew of any illicit conduct and sought to describe its rule
breaches as technical in nature. Mr Greg Palm, joint chief counsel, said
they occurred because information about the free payments 'was not
effectively combined with knowledge of the regulatory capital effect of such
a payment, giving rise to the computational and financial reporting errors'.
Goldman censured Page 6
Lex Page 22
</TEXT>
