<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUN 93 / London Stock Exchange: Royal Ins placing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEVE THOMPSON, JOEL KIBAZO and CHRISTINE BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Shares in Royal Insurance declined 5 to 283p after the rump of the recent
rights issue was placed by SG Warburg and Hoare Govett.
With an 87.2 per cent take-up of the issue reported, the outstanding 20.7m
shares were successfully placed with institutions at 281p. The impact of the
placing, along with general profit-taking, caused a retreat in the rest of
the sector. General Accident eased 7 to 576p, Commercial Union lost 8 to
589p, Sun Alliance closed 4 lighter at 357p and Legal &amp; General relinquished
6 to 460p.
Banking group Standard Chartered was the strong feature in banks after a
recommendation from SG Warburg sent the shares 15 ahead to 769p. Trading
was, however, thin.
The recommendation came after Monday's meeting with several analysts and
helped boost the stock that has underperformed the rest of the sector in
recent weeks. The rest of the banking group traded easier with the market.
Lloyds slipped 4 to 570p.
Another decline in crude oil prices continued to unsettle an oil sector
already weakened by the uneasy peace agreed at last week's Opec meeting in
Geneva. BP attracted a fresh wave of US sellers and settled 2 1/2 off at 307
1/2 p on turnover of 6.2m shares. Shell, in spite of the encouraging noises
from Monday's investment presentation, eased to 624p. Enterprise Oil dropped
9 more to 465p.
There was more downside pressure exerted on Zeneca, where the Pounds 1.3bn
rights issue closes next Monday. But dealers continue to take the view that
the issue is safe. 'It is a question of holding your nerve and waiting for
the reward,' was the view of one market optimist. Zeneca 'old' settled 1 1/2
off at 615 1/2 p on turnover of 3.7m, and the 'new' nil-paid eased a penny
to 16p with a hefty 8.2m shares traded. ICI, where the recent US buying
support has dried up, softened a penny to 706p.
Fisons extended its recent strong showing, the shares moving up strongly to
close a further 6 1/2 ahead at 168p on heavy turnover of 5.5m.
Guinness finished the day 8 lower at 485p as the acceptance was announced of
a management buyout at the South Wales-based Crown Brewery. Volume was
modest at 1.6m. Elsewhere, other large brewers suffered knocks, Bass losing
3 to 475p, Allied-Lyons giving up 6 to 539p and Grand Metropolitan dipping 6
to 413p.
Increased talk of takeovers stalked broadcasting shares, moving Anglia
Television up 12 to 329p, Central Independent ahead 7 to 1925p and Scottish
Television up 3 to 486p.
Reaction to its annual meeting statement pushed down Ladbroke by 6 1/2 to
171 1/2 p in turnover of 9.6m shares. One analyst said that the statement
was 'a shade disappointing' although he did not see any deep-rooted problems
with the leisure group, while another maintained that the shares had been
overpriced and were now beginning to find their level.
Ladbroke is a large player in the DIY aggressive pricing battle and its
statement revealed that its Texas Homecare chain had fallen short of trade
hopes so far this year.
Airtours moved forward 2 to 325p while Thorn EMI fell back 7 to 880p. David
Lloyd Leisure, which was floated in March in an issue that was seven times
oversubscribed, was bouyed by good results and advanced 13 to 191p.
After the High Court's refusal to sanction Mr Terry Venables' reinstatement
as chief executive of Tottenham Hotspur, the share price lost another penny
to 87p. It marks a slide of 7 in the stock, which is USM quoted, since the
boardroom battle between Mr Venables and Mr Alan Sugar resumed at the court
last week.
Confirmation by Coats Viyella that it has increased its holding in its
Indian subsidiary from 39.9 per cent to 51 per cent pushed up its share
price 4 to 230p in a volume of 1.6m. The Indian government granted
permission for the stake increase in the subsidiary, which is renamed Coats
Viyella India.
Courtaulds managed to close only a penny easier at 539p on a volume of 1.3m.
Among engineers and aerospace issues, continued profit-taking left British
Aerospace 7 down at 393p. Smiths Industries shed 3 to 357p following the
completion of a big buying order on Monday. Vickers put on 4 at 140p,
powered by a recommendation from SG Warburg. The 84 per cent jump in profits
at FKI had already been discounted by the market following the stock's
strong performance for most of this year. The shares eased 3 1/2 to 138p.
A talk-to-the-investors session and positive comments from NatWest
Securities enabled Unilever to push up 4 to 1048p with 2.6m shares traded.
Share price buoyancy of the company, which is optimistic about its growth in
East Asia, followed a strong showing on the previous day which had been
triggered by a similar presentation in Amsterdam last Friday.
Other gainers in food included Dalgety, which moved up 6 to 456p, albeit in
thin trading; United Biscuits, 2 firmer at 391p; and Unigate, which added 2
at 352p. A food analyst said investors were making tentative moves back to
the sector. But the picture was patchy - Cadbury-Schweppes lost 2 to 463p in
a volume of 1.7m; Tate &amp; Lyle moved down 2 to 384p; J. Sainsbury lost 2 to
484p in a small volume; and Tesco gave up 2 to finish at 217p on 2.9m
traded.
Volex was one of the best performers in the electricals/electronics areas of
the market, the shares racing up 18 to 405p after the doubled profits. News
that Quality Software, recently launched on the market, had won its first
order for its Universal Olas systems triggered a surge of buying interest in
the company's shares, which closed 32 higher at 558p.
</TEXT>
