<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUN 93 / International Company News: Kemper says brokerage is no
longer for sale
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN ZAGOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
KEMPER, the Chicago-based insurance and financial services company,
yesterday said its beleaguered Kemper Securities brokerage unit was no
longer for sale after it failed to receive an adequate offer for it.
'The offers simply didn't reflect the value inherent in this company and its
long-term prospects,' said Mr Stephen Timbers, Kemper's chief operating
officer.
Kemper Securities has long been considered a thorn in its parent's side.
Although the unit's performance improved in the 1993 first quarter, it has
lost more than Dollars 200m since 1982, with a deficit last year of Dollars
38.4m when many other brokerage houses posted record profits.
On May 27, Kemper said it was reviewing several expressions of interest from
parties considering acquiring Kemper Securities.
Kemper did not reveal specific plans for the securities division, but said
it would make a significant commitment to the business and added that it
would position the business to allows its management 'to demonstrate better
the operating performance of the unit'.
