<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUN 93 / Tory party to return Nadir funds if they were stolen
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON and DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CONSERVATIVE party pledged yesterday to return money donated to it by Mr
Asil Nadir if the funds proved to be stolen as it emerged that the fugitive
businessman is 'most unlikely' to return to Britain to face trial this
September.
In the first court hearing before Mr Justice Tucker since the former Polly
Peck chairman jumped bail and fled to northern Cyprus, the Serious Fraud
Office also ruled out any trial of Mr Nadir in his absence.
However, the SFO announced it would continue criminal proceedings against Mr
John Turner, the former Polly Peck group accountant facing false accounting
charges.
Conservative party officials promised that the Pounds 440,000 donated to
party funds by companies associated with Mr Nadir would be repaid if it were
proved that the money had been stolen. They also denied reports that Mr
Nadir had made other secret donations to party funds.
In an unusual statement released last night, the party said it received a
total of Pounds 440,000 over five years, with the last contribution made in
March 1990.
'These donations were not made by Mr Nadir personally but by Polly Peck
International plc or Unipac Packaging Ltd,' it said. 'We know of no other
donations from Mr Nadir personally or from his companies.'
Asked about allegations that Mr Nadir might have hoped the donations would
secure him a knighthood, party officials said no one had received an honour
for donating to the Conservative party. The sale of honours would be a
criminal offence, they said.
Officials said the party did not accept donations from sources that were not
clearly identified.
But comments made last night by Sir Brian Wyldbore-Smith, former director of
the party's treasury department, suggested this had not always been the
case. Sir Brian said he was 'very often' not aware of donors' identities.
In a crowded Old Bailey courtroom, Mr Anthony Scrivener QC, Mr Nadir's
barrister, said he had taken instructions from his client at 4pm on Monday.
'It is most unlikely he will be here for trial in September. I do not
propose to give reasons in open court,' he said.
Accepting the position, Mr Robert Owen QC, for the SFO, ruled out any
suggestion of putting Mr Nadir on trial in his absence.
'It would be entirely unprecedented. It would be entirely contrary to our
justice system. We submit it would be unthinkable,' he said. Mr Justice
Tucker agreed, saying such a move would not enhance the reputation of
British justice.
The judge also adjourned consideration of the possible forfeiting of Mr
Nadir's Pounds 3.5m bail sureties. The ownership of the Pounds 2m security
put up by Mr Nadir himself is currently the subject of an action in the
Chancery division of the High Court.
</TEXT>
