<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUN 93 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow declines in spite of good
inflation news
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
ANOTHER batch of good news on inflation failed to lift stock market
sentiment yesterday as blue chip issues fell and other stocks struggled to
hold their ground, writes Patrick Harverson in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average closed 22.69 down at 3,492.00. The Standard
&amp; Poor's 500 shed 1.44 to 446.27, while the Nasdaq composite was up a slight
0.93 at 697.34. New York SE volume was 234m shares.
After last week's promising May producer prices report, which suggested that
inflationary pressures in the economy were not as strong as originally
feared, dealers and investors were hoping that yesterday's May consumer
prices data would prove a similar source of comfort.
In the event, the numbers were encouraging: the Labor Department announced
that the consumer prices index rose by only 0.1 per cent last month, and
that the 'core' measure of prices (which excludes the volatile food and
energy components) was up by 0.2 per cent. The figures were slightly better
than forecast, and probably rule out the likelihood of an interest rate rise
by the Federal Reserve.
The good news, however, did not persuade investors to buy stocks. Concern
about the weak state of the economy, the absence of a big upward move in
bond prices, and a sharp decline in some leading stocks, meant the Dow
performed poorly and other indices languished.
IBM fell Dollars 2 to Dollars 50 in volume of 3m shares after Salomon
Brothers warned that there might be further write-offs at the company, which
could lead to IBM halving its dividend.
Among other Dow constituents to suffer yesterday were Merck, down Dollars
7/8 at Dollars 38, and cyclical stocks International Paper, off Dollars  7/8
at Dollars 63 1/2 , and Aluminium Company of America, Dollars 1 1/8 lower at
Dollars 65 1/2 .
Eastman Kodak, which rose sharply on Monday in anticipation of a big
announcement from the company, receded Dollars 1 3/8 to Dollars 52 3/8 in
turnover of 2.9m shares after it revealed plans to spin off its Eastman
Chemical subsidiary.
HJ Heinz lost Dollars  5/8 to Dollars 36 3/4 after announcing a Dollars 192m
pre-tax restructuring charge for the fiscal fourth quarter, which depressed
after-tax earnings for the quarter to Dollars 69.7m, down from Dollars
145.7m a year ago.
Reebok plunged Dollars 5 3/8 to Dollars 29 1/8 in busy trading as investors
reacted negatively to the company's warning that its second quarter earnings
will come in well below market estimates.
Tiffany jumped Dollars 2 7/8 to Dollars 31 3/8 on the news that it will
assume marketing and merchandising for 29 stores currently operated in Japan
by Mitsukoshi.
Canada
TORONTO ended higher after fairly heavy trading, boosted by a sharp rise in
gold shares. The TSE 300 index gained 15.6 at 3,887.8 and rises led falls by
387 to 339 after volume of 59.5m shares valued at CDollars 585.2m.
Turnover included a block trade of about 5.4m Talisman Energy shares. The
golds sector index jumped 4.16 per cent as the New York spot gold price rose
USDollars 4.20 an ounce.
</TEXT>
