<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUN 93 / Warburg seeks cash dealing in BT shares
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent, STEVE THOMPSON and ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE London Stock Exchange, at the request of merchant bank SG Warburg, is
asking marketmakers in British Telecommunications shares to take the
unprecedented step of accepting dealings in the shares on a cash settlement
basis. The move would allow Warburg, the global co-ordinator in the sale of
the third tranche of the government's stake in BT, to learn who had bought
or sold BT shares before share allocations were announced.
Dealings for cash settlement are known within 48 hours while under the
account settlement system, it takes two weeks. Thus, sellers of shares will
be identified. Those judged by BT's advisers to have sold in an effort to
depress the price will be allocated fewer shares in the BT3 issue.
In a letter dated June 11 to marketmakers in BT shares, the stock exchange
said it is asking for their co-operation 'to ensure that the existing Fully
Paid register is as up to date as possible'.
'Warburgs have requested that the Exchange recommend dealings in the two
trading accounts prior to the close of the offer (in mid July) take place on
a Cash Settlement basis. The Exchange are prepared to support this in
principle.'
The stock exchange has told marketmakers that those who do not respond by
today will be assumed to agree.
Last night, the exchange said it did not know the results of its poll of
marketmakers. However, a Warburg official said: 'The feedback we've had has
not been negative.'
News of the Warburg move has led to strong protests from some institutional
shareholders and marketmakers. They argued that such disclosure will
discourage sellers, thereby tending to support the BT share price during the
bidding process for the BT3 shares. They say the move stops them selling
shares, normal practice in the run-up to a new issue.
The absence of this selling will tend to support the BT share price before
the bidding process for BT3 shares.
But Warburg insists its request is not intended to uncover sellers, only
buyers, so that it may reward them with higher allocations of new shares.
Lex, Page 20
</TEXT>
