<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUN 93 / Shares in water up on Wessex results
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANGUS FOSTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE privatised UK water sector, overshadowed recently by regulatory worries,
rallied yesterday after better-than-expected results from Wessex Water, one
of the smallest of the 10 companies.
Wessex reported a 12 per cent increase in pre-tax profits from Pounds 76.9m
to Pounds 86m in the year to March 31. Wessex's shares gained 12p to 570p.
Other water companies which have seen their shares fall sharply in the last
month, such as North West and Welsh, rose by as much as 3 per cent.
Mr Nicholas Hood, chairman, said the results were 'excellent'. 'I'm proud of
it, but not smug,' he said.
Wessex's unregulated businesses, mainly the joint venture with Waste
Management International of the US, performed well, contributing Pounds 7.1m
after interest costs compared with Pounds 2.7m last year. Another
unregulated business, contractor Wimpey Wessex, recorded a Pounds 200,000
loss on a contract and is to be closed.
Group turnover increased 8 per cent, in line with average price increases,
to Pounds 205.6m. Operating costs were unchanged and helped toward a 20 per
cent increase in operating profits of Pounds 81m.
In January, Wessex raised Pounds 144.5m through a rights issue and other
funding to pay for its share of the acquisition cost of the waste arm of
NFC, the transport group. Proceeds from the issue helped improve Wessex's
net cash position from Pounds 15m to Pounds 54m by the year end. However,
the timing of cash flows made interest income fall sharply, from Pounds 8.5m
to Pounds 500,000.
Capital expenditure on improving water and sewerage quality peaked at Pounds
130m. Depreciation increased 10 per cent to Pounds 21.1m.
Streamlining acquisitions led to cost savings which were expected to
continue. Mr Hood said price increases of between 5 and 15 per cent had been
achieved at some of the landfills acquired through the NFC purchase.
Fully diluted earnings were affected by a higher tax charge and increased 6
per cent to 60.1p. The company recommended a final dividend of 14.2p to make
a total of 21.5p, an increase of 10 per cent. Mr Hood said the increase was
partly justified by the rising contribution from unregulated businesses.
Lex, Page 20
</TEXT>
