<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUN 93 / HJ Heinz moves to cut costs worldwide
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
HJ HEINZ, the US food group, yesterday announced a range of cost-cutting
moves, involving an 8 per cent reduction in its worldwide workforce of
35,500 and a cut in its UK operations.
The company will take a Dollars 192m (Pounds 124m) pre-tax charge against
fourth-quarter earnings to pay for the shake-up.
Heinz's chairman, Mr Tony O'Reilly, claimed the latest restructuring charge
would help Heinz speed up productivity improvements, and concentrate a
three-year rationalisation programme into 12 months. Analysts, however, saw
the action as further evidence of the pressures which the
intensely-competitive retail sector is putting on the big consumer product
companies.
'All the food companies are responding to the pressure by accelerating this
sort of restructuring,' said Mr Les Pugh at Salomon Brothers in New York,
noting that the anticipated operational efficiencies were not expected to
bring much additional earnings growth.
Specific changes include: shifts in manufacturing capacity between Canada
and US; a reduction in operations in the UK, Italy, and in the Ore-Ida
division; a cut of about 30 per cent, or 240 jobs, at a plant south of
Melbourne, Australia; the consolidation of North American sales service
functions in one Pittsburgh-based operation; and a merging of the US
administrative back-up for Heinz Pet Products and Starkist, the tuna
business.
The charge meant that operating profits in the final three months of Heinz's
financial year to April 28, fell to Dollars 54.8m, compared with Dollars
230.5m a year ago, on sales of Dollars 2.03bn (up from Dollars 1.87bn). For
the full year, operating profits were down from Dollars 1.11bn to Dollars
860.9m, with sales rising from Dollars 6.58bn to Dollars 7.1bn.
The cost-cutting will be spread across Heinz operations worldwide and,
although the company declined to put a firm figure on the potential jobs
losses, could prune the workforce by up to 3,000. At the end of its 1992
financial year, Heinz had 35,500 employees.
The fourth-quarter operating profit of Dollars 54.8m translated into an
after-tax surplus of Dollars 69.7m, compared with Dollars 145.7m a year ago.
For the 12 months, Heinz' net profits stood at Dollars 396.3m, after a
Dollars 133.6m charge for the adoption of the new accounting standard on
post-retirement benefits. In 1991-2, the figure was Dollars 638.3m.
</TEXT>
