<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUN 93 / Male claims of discrimination in job market increase sharply
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SEX discrimination complaints at work soared by nearly two-thirds last year.
For the first time, men formed a large proportion of those claiming
companies were biased in their hiring policies.
The Equal Opportunities Commission, which published its 1992 annual report
yesterday said there had been a 64 per cent increase over the previous year
in complaints about workplace discrimination. The most common allegations
concerned recruitment, terms and conditions, and sexual harassment.
Of the 1,253 complaints to the commission about companies' hiring policies,
40 per cent had been from men, said the EOC. Ms Valerie Amos, chief
executive, said the recession had made men 'much more aware of their
rights'. Those men complaining about being turned down for jobs were
typically aged 55 to 60 and redundancy victims.
High male unemployment and greater opportunities in service-sector
industries had driven men to seek jobs in traditionally female areas of
work, said the EOC.
Analysis of information gathered from about 400,000 employers by the
Department of Employment, published last month, indicated that in 11 UK
areas, women were now more likely to go to work than men, although nearly
half of jobs done by women were part-time. Separate government figures show
there are almost as many women in the workforce as men.
The commission warned companies not to discriminate against men applying for
traditionally 'women's' jobs after a 50-year-old man was turned down for a
post in a children's nursery last year. He later won Pounds 600 at an
industrial tribunal.
Overall, the commission reported a 47 per cent increase, to 13,320, in the
number of inquiries over the past year. The 'discriminatory practices of
many employers who are shedding labour during the recession undoubtedly
added to the EOC's load,' says the annual report.
</TEXT>
