<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUN 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Remember that parody? 'Say what you will, school dinners make you ill, and
shepherd's pie got Davy Crockett down, our school din-dins come from pig
bins, out of town.' By all accounts today's school children are more likely
to be offered pizza and chips than shepherd's pie. BBC2's access slot Open
Space ends an interesting series with a programme lamenting the
deterioration of that great British institution, the school dinner (7.55).
That is followed at 8.25 by Freya Stark, the first of two repeated
documentaries celebrating the life and work of the extraordinary writer and
traveller who died last month. In 1982, when she was 90, Freya Stark was
visited in her family home in the hills north of Venice by John Julius
Norwich who talked to her of her bohemian childhood and her achievements as
an explorer. Dispatches (9.00 C4) claims that it will reveal the identity of
Deep Throat, the hitherto anonymous source whose information enabled
Washington Post reporters Woodward and Bernstein to blow open the American
political scandal which came to be known as Watergate.
</TEXT>
