<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUN 93 / Parliament and Politics: PM targets invalidity claimants
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT'S determination to press ahead with proposals for restricting
expenditure on invalidity benefit was emphasised by Mr John Major, the prime
minister, in the Commons yesterday.
He said the number of benefit claimants had more than doubled over the past
10. He said it beggared belief that 'so many more people have suddenly
become invalids, especially at a time when the health of the nation has
improved'.
Mr Major told jeering Labour MPs: 'I make no apologies for looking at this
area of expenditure'.
Undeterred by fierce protests from Labour MPs, he said the number of people
receiving invalidity benefit had more than doubled over the last 10 years
from 700,000 to 1.5m while spending had gone up from about Pounds 1.5bn to
over Pounds 6bn. 'No responsible government could ignore an increase of that
order,' he insisted.
Earlier, Mr Major discussed proposals for cutting the Pounds 50bn public
sector borrowing requirement with Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, Mr
Michael Portillo, chief secretary to the Treasury, Mr Peter Lilley, social
security secretary, and Mr Michael Forsyth, employment minister, at 10
Downing Street.
Labour MPs based their onslaught on last week's disclosure that, in a draft
letter, Mr Lilley outlined proposals for taxing invalidity benefit, focusing
it more on the long-term sick, as well as making it less generous and
subject to a tough medical test.
According to government estimates these changes would save Pounds 495m in
the 1996-97 financial year, and Pounds 1.3bn by the year 2000.
While Downing Street officials indicated than no decisions were taken at
yesterday's ministerial meeting, new rules are likely to be in place when
the chancellor presents his November budget.
In the Commons the prime minister faced a blunt demand from Mr Ian Davidson
(Lab Glasgow Govan) to sack any minister who proposed 'a drastic reduction
in the already inadequate level of invalidity benefit'.
Mr Major immediately confirmed that invalidity benefit was being considered
by ministers, and maintained that they were 'entirely right' to do so.
Mr Donald Dewar, the shadow social security secretary, said later the prime
minister had made it 'all too clear' that Labour had been right to accuse
the government of planning a Treasury 'raid' on the long-term sick.
He accused the prime minister of showing no understanding of the problems of
those facing illness, and he urged Mr Major to recognise that high
unemployment was the root cause of his problems.
</TEXT>
