<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUN 93 / Parliament and Politics: Tendering threshold set for
councils
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SMALL councils need not put white-collar services out to tender where the
scale of the activity is below a certain level, the government said
yesterday, Alison Smith writes.
Mr David Curry, the local government minister, said that the de minimis
threshold could be based on the value of a particular service, on the number
of staff employed in performing it, or a combination of the two factors.
Tendering for the first tranche of white-collar services - those related to
construction - is due to begin in late spring next year.
The decision to set a threshold would not prevent councils from putting such
services out to tender if they wanted to, but would mean that they were not
required to incur the costs of the tendering process if they thought the
likely benefit too small.
</TEXT>
