<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUN 93 / Growth trend in manufacturing 'up from 4% to 5%'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MANUFACTURING output recovered in April and is growing faster than at any
time since May 1989, the government reported yesterday.
The Central Statistical Office said manufacturing production grew by a
seasonally adjusted 0.7 per cent between March and April after a 0.3 per
cent decline in March. This prompted CSO statisticians to revise upwards
their estimate of the annual trend rate of growth from 4 per cent to 5 per
cent.
All manufacturing sectors increased output in the three months to April
compared with the previous three months, lifting the manufacturing
production index out of its previous narrow range.
The Treasury welcomed the figures as a further sign that economic recovery
is under way. A breakdown of the figures suggests that recovery is being led
by investment, and possibly exports, rather than by consumer demand.
The CSO said manufacturing production increased by a seasonally adjusted 2.2
per cent between February and April compared with the previous three-month
period. It was also 2.2 per cent higher than in the three months to April
last year. Manufacturing production in April was at its highest since
January 1991.
April's figures were buoyed by strong growth in the output of steel, metals,
and computers.
Taking the latest three months' figures, which the CSO's statisticians
consider a better guide, the office reported strong increases in the
production of cars, computers and aerospace equipment, as well as materials
for the building industry and packaging.
Production of cars and parts rose 8.1 per cent in the three months to April
compared with the previous three months, while output of computers increased
by 14 per cent over the same period.
Overall production of investment goods grew strongly, with output up 3.4 per
cent in the three months to April compared with the previous three months,
reflecting increases of 5.7 per cent and 5.3 per cent respectively in the
production of the electrical goods and transport equipment industries.
Investment goods production in the three months to April was 5.4 per cent
higher than the year before.
Consumer goods output was less buoyant, in spite of the sharp rise in car
production. It rose 1.1 per cent in the three months to April compared with
the previous period, and was 1.3 per cent higher than a year before.
Extended maintenance work in the North Sea caused a 5 per cent drop in oil
and natural gas production in the three months to April compared with
November to January.
Other energy production dropped by 2.4 per cent as mild weather caused a
decline in gas and electricity output. Coal output fell 8 per cent between
March and April as lower supply contracts between British Coal and the big
electricity generating companies took effect.
The drop in energy production offset the rise in manufacturing output so
that total combined production of the manufacturing and energy industries
was unchanged between March and April. Overall industrial production rose
0.6 per cent in the last three months.
</TEXT>
